          <div class="row d-flex justify-content-center">
          <p class="parrafo col-8 col-xl-8 col-lg-8 col-md-6 col-sm-8">- <b>Graph 1:</b> the bar graph represents the annual precipitations expected in the Guadalquivir basin for the years 2012-2021 and the amount it really received.<br>
            - <b>Graph 2:</b> the line graph represents the growth in the amount of berries plantes in Huelva between 2010 and 2019.<br>
            - <b>Graph 3:</b> the scrollytelling images show the evolution of Laguna de Santa Olalla in 2004, 2011 and 2020.<br>
            - <b>Graph 4:</b> the image shows how many greenhouses are inside the national park the its borders.<br>
            - <b>Graph 5:</b> the image shows the proportions that the greenhouses inside and near the park have and how big the are compared to the village of El Rocío (in yellow).<br>
            - <b>Graph 6:</b> the line graph shows the evolution that irrigation olives has had in the province of Córdoba between 2010 and 2019.<br>
            - <b>Graph 7:</b> the bar graph represent the maximum capacity of the biggest reservoirs in the Guadalquivir bassin, the amount of water they had in January 2012 and how much they had ten years later.<br>
            - <b>Graph 8:</b> it shows the water level of Iznájar’s reservoir (the biggest in Andalusia) in June 2016 and november 2021.</p>
